OSU Student News Use Survey

Jacob Long
2020-02-21

The following reports the results of a survey of 456 Ohio State students starting their second year on campus conducted in November 2019. This population was chosen because at this point, their news routines should be relatively set in stone and this cohort is one that was given iPads, which gave them all an opportunity to access The Lantern via its pre-installed app.

Note: All statistics reported here are after weighting to match student demographics in terms of gender, transfer status, and in-state/out-of-state/international status. The margin of error for proportions is approximately 5%. The response rate for the survey was 9.1%.

Summary

  • Nearly all students use major social media platforms, but few gets news from them.
  • Few students get news anywhere but online.
  • Students know about The Lantern, but only about half say they ever get news from it.
  • A majority of students think The Lantern is not editorially independent of the university.
  • Nearly two-thirds of students say they didn’t know there was a The Lantern app on their iPads.
  • Most who knew about The Lantern app say they’ve never opened it.
  • Students rely mostly on friends and classmates for OSU news, with Twitter and Instagram also as common sources.

General news habits

First, we want to know how students relate to news in general. They seem to have wide-ranging interests.

On the other hand, they are not using legacy media.

But online, they are more idiosyncratic in terms of their preferences for news formats.

They are using social media, but many are not using these platforms for news.

For another way to look at this, we can break it down by each response to get a look at the intensity of opinion. Below we can see there’s a big group of people who really care about sports, despite there being a larger-than-normal group who really don’t care about sports. And not too many are really enthused about campus events, but nobody feels like they don’t care either.

No clear story when it comes to entertainment interests, but there will be an audience for several kinds of local-oriented coverage.
